SWOW-RP Descriptives

Participants

There were 67148 participants in total (17.2% males, 81.8% females and 1% other) with an average age of 38.3 (SD = 15.2, min = 5, max = 99). Participants were excluded based on several demographic and response criteria. First, only participants aged 16 and older were retained. Next, participants responses that provided the same response to several cues in the list were excluded. Participants who indicated over 70% of words as either unknown or missing were excluded. Finally, participants who responded with over 30% of multiword phrases or where fewer than 60% of words were not in a Spanish word list were also excluded. The total number of excluded participants amounted to 10.3% of the original sample.

Demographic details

Further details about the retained participants sample are shown in Figure 1 and 2. Figure 1 shows the geolocation of participants in Uruguay and Argentina, together relative to the distribution worldwide. Most participants spoke the Rioplatense variant (Argentina: XX%, Uruguay, YY%), followed by Cordobes (XX%) and Nor-oriental Guarani (XX%). The majority of participants were in Argentina or Uruguay at the moment of testing, with the largest proportion outside of these countries in XX (X%) and YY (Y%).

Figure 2 shows the breakdown interaction between age, gender and education.

 

Cues

The dataset consists of 13457 cue words and included 206 proper nouns.

Responses

Missing and unknown responses

On average, 3.3 % of the cue trials were judged unknown (min = 0%, max = 59%). The 10 most unknown words are {anatema, cisma, otredad, procrastinar, perimido}. Missing (i.e. “No more responses”) R2 responses occurred on average on 17% of cases. For R3, an average of 8% of cases were missing. Cues had at least 174 and at most 210 responses.

Coverage

For each cue, the coverage was calculated as the percentage of responses that were part of the list of cue words. The average coverage for all (R123) responses was 87.2% (min = 47%, max = 99.3%). The top 10 words with the lowest coverage are {entregar, vasto, agradable, humano, individuo}.

Response Distribution and centrality

For each cue the entropy of the response distribution was calculated as \(H(X_{cue}) = - \sum_{i=1}^n P(x_i)log_2P(x_i)\) and normalized by the information length. Cues with high entropy R123 response distributions were {polar, inmediatamente, símil, ordeñar, adicionar}, and cues with the lowest entropy were {intolerancia, mala gente, aburridos, mezclas, vagos}.

Central responses are responses that are given for either for a large number of cues (type frequency) or are given frequently across all cues (token frequency).

As before, all results are based on R123 responses. The top 10 most common response types were {agua, comida, amor, trabajo, dolor, dinero, música, animal, vida, casa}. These were highly similar to the most common responses tokens: {amor, trabajo, vida, persona, dolor, comida, familia, tiempo, malo, personas}.
